						<summary>

						<p>The king's name which is damaged ends in <hi rend="bold">varsha.</hi> Since the record is <hi rend="bold">dated in Śaka 759 (= A.D. 837),</hi> it may be assigned to the reign of <hi rend="bold">Amōghavarsha I</hi> (A.D. 814-15 to 877-78). It mentions a daughter (name<note n="4-1">This may be read as<ka>rēvakka.</ka></note>lost) of the king who was perhaps the wife of <hi rend="bold">Yeṟagaṅga</hi> who was ruling over the <hi rend="bold">Eḍadoṟe</hi> and other districts.</p>						

						<p>The details of date given in ll. 1—4 and 23-24 are: Śaka 759 (expired), Jyēshṭha, ba. 14, Wednesday. The given <hi rend="italic">tithi</hi> fell on Tuesday (not Wednesday), ·90. The date would correspond to A.D. 837, June 5, Tuesday. The cyclic year must be Piṅgaḷa.</p>						

						</summary>
					</msContents>
